andson, Richard FitzGilbert, accompanied William the Conqueror and was made Lord of Clare. His great-grandson was Robert FitzWalter, one of the barons who guaranteed the Magna Carta in 1215."]},{"name":"Walter","meanings":["English (of Norman origin), German, Dutch, Polish, Swedish, and Danish: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This personal name was introduced into England both in the reign of Edward the Confessor and by the Normans (in the forms <i>Walt(i)er</i>, <i>Waut(i)er</i>). After the Norman Conquest it soon became one of the most popular personal names in Britain. Compare   Walther  .","Germanized or Americanized form of Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian <b>Valter</b> and Czech <b>Valtr</b>: from the personal name <i>Valter</i>, <i>Valtr</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"Radigund","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>gund</i> ‘strife’."],"variants":[{"name":"Radegunde","meanings":["from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>gund</i> ‘strife’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Radigund FitzWalter was born in 1391, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with James Chudleigh. She died in 1461, in her hometown, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1391–1461":"1391–1461","1387–1457":"1387–1457","14